description:
On a mid-stream service error or a chunk-encode failure, both streaming handlers emit `event: error
data: {}

` — an empty object. The underlying `LlmError` (Unauthorized, RateLimited, Network, BackendError with the provider's body) is dropped entirely. A client receiving `data: {}` cannot distinguish rate-limiting from auth failure from a transport blip, and nothing is logged either, so operators are blind to streaming-path failures.

verifierNote:
Confirmed in crates/solobase-core/src/blocks/llm/routes.rs. The quoted code is exact: handle_chat_stream (lines 326-340) and load_model (lines 736-746) both use `let Ok(..) = item else { emit b"event: error
data: {}

"; return }` for the stream-error arm and the JSON-encode arm. Both discard the error and never log. The asymmetry the reviewer claims is real: the buffered handle_chat path (line 228) routes errors through err_internal, which tracing::error!-logs the full cause with a correlation ID; the streaming arms do neither (the only two tracing calls in the file are lines 248 and 430, neither in an error arm), so operators are blind to streaming-path failures and the client gets a content-free `data: {}`. One factual correction to the reviewer: the discarded error is a wafer_core WaferError (carries ErrorCode + message), NOT an `LlmError` enum with `Unauthorized/RateLimited/Network/BackendError` variants — that named type/variant list is inaccurate at this layer, though the substance (a typed error with code+message is dropped) holds. Real but I downgrade medium->low: there is no security/correctness defect (stream still terminates with a clean error frame; consumers can distinguish error from [DONE]), and the reviewer's recommendation to serialize the raw error message into the SSE frame partly conflicts with err_internal's deliberate client-message sanitization policy — emitting a code (e.g. `{"error":"<ErrorCode>"}`) plus adding the missing tracing::warn! is the right fix. The genuine gap is the missing server-side log + empty client payload, an observability/code-quality issue, not a high-impact bug.
